Review dimension: Code Quality
Severity: medium
File: Controllers/FilesController.cs:188-243
Title: Execute and ExecuteAsync duplicate the same five catch→BadRequest clauses

Finding:
Execute(Func<ActionResult>) and ExecuteAsync(Func<Task<ActionResult>>) each independently repeat the identical five catch clauses (ArgumentException, UnauthorizedAccessException, DirectoryNotFoundException, FileNotFoundException, IOException), each translating to BadRequest(new { error = ex.Message }) — ten near-identical catch blocks total. This is a DRY violation with a real drift risk: if the translatable-exception set ever changes (e.g. adding PathTooLongException by name, or removing one), an author must remember to update both methods identically or the sync and async endpoints will diverge. Notably the controller's own tests (FilesControllerTests.CaughtExceptions) enumerate the exact catch list and comment that "the extracted helper must preserve" it — indicating a single shared translator was the intended design. The two methods differ only in await body() vs body(), which is trivially unifyable.

Fix instructions (follow exactly; make targeted, minimal changes):
In Controllers/FilesController.cs, eliminate the duplicated exception translation. Extract a single helper that maps a caught exception to a BadRequest (or null when it should propagate), e.g. `private static ActionResult? TranslateKnownException(Exception ex)` returning BadRequest(new { error = ex.Message }) for ArgumentException, UnauthorizedAccessException, DirectoryNotFoundException, FileNotFoundException, and IOException (in that order, preserving the existing catch precedence), and null otherwise. Then have both Execute and ExecuteAsync use it: Execute does `try { return body(); } catch (Exception ex) { return TranslateKnownException(ex) ?? throw; }` and ExecuteAsync does `try { return await body(); } catch (Exception ex) { return TranslateKnownException(ex) ?? throw; }`. Preserve the existing XML doc comments (including the note about why the return type is ActionResult), keep the same exception→400 mapping and message payload, and keep non-translated exceptions propagating unchanged. Run dotnet test TestProject.Tests/TestProject.Tests.csproj afterward; the existing CaughtExceptions/error-path tests in FilesControllerTests.cs must still pass (they pin this exact behavior).

